  <h1>Tax Glossary</h1>

  <h2>A</h2>
    <p><strong>Adjusted Gross Income</strong> — Gross income reduced by certain amounts, such as a deductible IRA contribution or student loan interest.</p>
    <p><strong>Amount Due</strong> — The total amount of tax owed after all credits and payments have been applied.</p>
    <p><strong>Audit</strong> — An examination of an individual's or organization's financial information by the IRS to ensure that income and deductions are reported accurately and comply with tax laws.</p>

  <h2>B</h2>
    <p><strong>Bonus</strong> — Compensation received by an employee for services performed, given in addition to usual compensation.</p>

  <h2>D</h2>
    <p><strong>Direct Deposit</strong> — An electronic method of transferring funds directly into a recipient's bank account, often used for tax refunds or payroll payments.</p>

  <h2>E</h2>
    <p><strong>Earned Income</strong> — Income received from working, including wages, salaries, tips, and net earnings from self-employment.</p>
    <p><strong>Electronic Filing (E-filing)</strong> — The process of submitting tax returns to the IRS electronically, often through tax software or a tax professional.</p>

  <h2>F</h2>
    <p><strong>FICA (Federal Insurance Contributions Act)</strong> — Provides benefits for retired workers and their dependents as well as for disabled workers and their dependents. Also known as the Social Security tax.</p>
    <p><strong>Filing Status</strong> — A category that defines the type of tax return form an individual will use, based on their marital status and family situation (e.g., Single, Married Filing Jointly, Head of Household).</p>
    <p><strong>Form W-4, Employee's Withholding Allowance Certificate</strong> — Completed by the employee and used by the employer to determine the amount of income tax to withhold.</p>

  <h2>G</h2>
    <p><strong>Gross Income</strong> — Total income from all sources before any deductions or taxes are applied.</p>

  <h2>M</h2>
    <p><strong>Medicare Tax</strong> — A payroll tax that funds the Medicare program, typically calculated as a percentage of an employee's wages.</p>

  <h2>P</h2>
    <p><strong>Payroll Taxes</strong> — Taxes imposed on employers and employees, usually calculated as a percentage of the salaries that employers pay their staff. These taxes fund Social Security and Medicare.</p>
    <p><strong>Progressive Tax</strong> — A tax system in which the tax rate increases as the taxable amount increases, meaning that higher-income earners pay a larger percentage of their income in taxes than lower-income earners.</p>

  <h2>R</h2>
    <p><strong>Refund</strong> — The amount of money returned to a taxpayer when the amount of tax paid exceeds the tax liability.</p>

  <h2>S</h2>
    <p><strong>Standard Deduction</strong> — A fixed dollar amount that reduces the income on which you are taxed, available to most taxpayers who do not itemize deductions.</p>

  <h2>T</h2>
    <p><strong>Tax Avoidance</strong> — The legal use of tax laws to reduce one's tax liability, such as by claiming deductions and credits.</p>
    <p><strong>Tax Credit</strong> — A dollar-for-dollar reduction in the tax. Can be deducted directly from taxes owed.</p>
    <p><strong>Tax Deduction</strong> — An amount (often a personal or business expense) that reduces income subject to tax.</p>
    <p><strong>Tax Evasion</strong> — The illegal act of not paying taxes owed, often by underreporting income or inflating deductions.</p>
    <p><strong>Tax Liability</strong> — The amount of tax that must be paid. Taxpayers meet (or pay) their federal income tax liability through withholding, estimated tax payments, and payments made with the tax forms they file with the government.</p>
    <p><strong>Taxable Income</strong> — The portion of your income that is subject to taxation after deductions and exemptions are applied.</p>

  <h2>W</h2>
    <p><strong>Wages</strong> — Compensation received by an employee for services performed, typically reported on a W-2 form.</p>
    <p><strong>Withholding</strong> — The amount of an employee's wages that an employer sends directly to the government as partial payment of the employee's tax liability.</p>

